We present results from a meta-analysis of 95 experimental and quasi-experimental preK-12 science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM) professional development and curriculum programs, seeking to estimate average program impact and to understand what content, activities and formats relate to stronger student outcomes. We found that rigorously conducted studies of STEM instructional improvement programs documented an average positive effect on student achievement, with a mean pooled effect size across studies of 0.21 SD. 

We conducted a series of analyses to examine the relationships between program characteristics and the size of achievement impacts.  The characteristics that were significantly associated with improved student learning across the current set of studies included:

Professional development combined with new curriculum materials; 
Content designed to improve teachers' content/pedagogical content knowledge, or understanding of how students learn; 
Specific formats, including: 

meetings to troubleshoot and discuss classroom implementation of the program;
the provision of summer workshops to begin the professional development learning process; 
same-school collaboration.




We also found that on average, programs that provided any component of the PD online had poorer student outcomes than programs that did not use an online PD component. In general, there was not a statistically significant difference in the magnitudes of program impacts depending on whether programs focused on mathematics or science, and no variability in impact size by features of curriculum materials. 

Many of the specific programs associated with improved student learning in our review are unlikely to accessible to the typical U.S. teacher, making research on local professional development and curriculum implementation imperative.  In addition, studies included in our analyses typically provided little information about how district and school contexts interact to support or impede these programs, leaving us with unanswered questions about how local educators can maximize program efficacy. Thus future experimental studies that build on the current findings are warranted, to advance researchers' and policymakers' understanding of key supports for improving student learning in STEM at scale.





